by Kiu Ghesik » Sat Oct 31, 2020 3:25 pm

Hamatu wrote:If I understand it right, Ari's name could also be Akhens-Ardri and it'd mean the same thing?
Also, that I'm apparently really bad at finding Easter eggs!(Although, it is really cool that the heading links already work)

It could be. The -ri/-dri suffix is largely based on both my personal preference and the length of the name; "arah", the base, is a very short name so Ari flows better. "Vhiar" also becomes "Vhiari" because "Vhiar" ends in an r. But, say, "Vashah" would become "Vashadri", so it's possible it can be based on whether or not the base name ends in a consonant or a vowel. I haven't made the list of modifiers in the official factbook yet, though, because I'm not confident in my grasp of the terminology and mechanics of it all yet.

If I were to define it as a consistent application, it would be as such:

If the word's last consonant is "r", then the female suffix is "-ri". If the word's last consonant is not "r", then the female suffix is "-dri".

(And yes, I'm very glad I could get the links to work as well, though they were a pain to figure out, since to make them the same color I had to re-make the color and font tags for each new header and that added a good twenty minutes to the creation process since it took me a while to un-tangle the BBCode. I'm still not sure why fonts and colors don't carry over into URL tags, but they don't, for whatever reason.)

Thanks for asking!

The Easter eggs are largely in the names of some of the words - "and" being translated as "it" - and some of the pronunciations. "Arah" is basically pronounced the same as "ara", something I realized after I'd decided on the infinitive verb form, and as such saying "To cry, to cry!" in Ghesite would literally be saying ara-ara.

You're free to crucify me now.

by Kiu Ghesik » Sat Oct 31, 2020 8:21 pm

Vadterland wrote:
Kiu Ghesik wrote:Socialism for these people is literally a synonym for "corrupt and ineffectual dictatorship", apparently.

The Kiu Ghesik are a clan-based nomadic society, not unlike pre-modern Mongols, Turks, and Berbers, who are currently in the technological equivalent of the late Bronze Age and inhabit a steppe region. Their religion is also akin to these aforementioned groups, revolving around a sky deity, although this time a Sky Mother rather than a Sky Father is the central figure, whose will is interpreted via the winds and clouds.

Correct!

There's also a bit of deism and Chinese mythology thrown in there to balance out the Tengrism, in addition to some unique philosophy; Mummy Tengri is much more mechanical as a deity, Earth is not seen as a meeting ground between an upper and lower plane (i.e., no Tengri v. Eje dynamic), and the religion's view of humanity is far less steady- people live to die and only to die, and divine intervention is rare; what happens happens, we have no control over the broad scope of things, and nothing we build can ever last, as it is man's God-given role to die and fade away, just as all things in the lower sphere are meant to.

New Dunmore wrote:Their religion, while technically monotheistic in nature, believe that the winds are living beings that actively, though only minorly, shape the world around them. They could be compared to minor gods, such as river deities, and have traits loosely based on the actual quality of the wind itself (unless I misread it). Along with this, they actively practice a form of Aeromancy through the reading of cloud formations.

Also correct!

Though I would note that it's not magic- it's a very basic form of meteorology with mysticism heaped on top of it. You're completely correct on everything else, though.
